03664nam a22005175i 9780773566811DE-B159720230529101353.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t19971997xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735668117 a10.1515/97807735668112doi  a(DE-B1597)656934  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aPN721bH54 1997eb 7aLIT0000002bisacsh04a809/.933841 aHill, John Spencer, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aInfinity, Faith, and Time :bChristian Humanism and Renaissance Literature /cJohn Spencer Hill. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[1997] 4c©1997  a1 online resource (216 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMcGill-Queen's Studies in the History of Religion ;v2900tFront Matter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tThe Expanding Universe -- tFides Quærens Intellectum -- tThe Aristotelian Cosmos -- tNicholas of Cusa and the New Astronomy -- tRational Spirituality and Empirical Rationalism -- tChorismos and Methexis: Pascal, Traherne, Milton -- tTime -- tChronos and Kairos -- tInner Time: Augustine and Bergson -- tTime, Literature, and Literary Criticism -- tTime in Shakespeare -- tHeilsgeschischte: Typology and the Helix of History -- tNotes Toward a Protestant Poetic -- tTranslations from Pascal’s Pensées -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn Part 1 Hill examines the effect of the idea of spatial infinity on seventeenth-century literature, arguing that the metaphysical cosmology of Nicholas of Cusa provided Renaissance writers, such as Pascal, Traherne, and Milton, with a way to construe the vastness of space as the symbol of human spiritual potential. Focusing on time in Part 2, Hill reveals that, faced with the inexorability of time, Christian humanists turned to St Augustine to develop a philosophy that interpreted temporal passage as the necessary condition of experience without making it the essence or ultimate measure of human purpose. Hill's analysis centres on Shakespeare, whose experiments with the shapes of time comprise a gallery of heuristic time-centred fictions that attempt to explain the consequences of human existence in time. Infinity, Faith, and Time reveals that the sixteenth and seventeenth centuries were a period during which individuals were able, with more success than in later times, to make room for new ideas without rejecting old beliefs.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aChristianity and literature. 0aEuropean literatureyRenaissance, 1450-1600xHistory and criticism. 0aHumanism in literature. 0aInfinite in literature. 0aTime in literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077356681140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773566811423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773566811/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles